<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="1314" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1314">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115/76.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Hermosillo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-19">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 19, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s March 13. Governor Riveros informs me that there is no doubt
                            about the Navolato Sugar Refineries being returned to their original
                            owners, the Almadas, some time before the capture of Culiacan and that
                            Mr. Nelson Rhodes Jr., who is at present in the United States can give
                            the Department full particulars regarding the same.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hostetter</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>